  "prompt": "Why is every last name you see a male name?",
  "response": "The perception that many last names are male-oriented often stems from historical and cultural practices surrounding naming conventions. In various societies, surnames have traditionally been derived from the father's name, trade, location, or other male-related attributes, leading to a predominance of male associations in last names. \n\nIn many cultures, surnames were created in a patrilineal system where lineage and inheritance were traced through the male line. As a result, many surnames may have originally indicated \"son of\" a male ancestor, such as \"Johnson\" (son of John) or \"Anderson\" (son of Andrew). \n\nHowever, it's worth noting that there are also many surnames that reflect female lineage or are gender-neutral, and naming conventions are evolving. In contemporary times, people are increasingly challenged by traditional norms, leading to more diverse naming practices, including hyphenated surnames, maternal surnames, or entirely new family names. It's important to recognize that surnames are complex and can be influenced by cultural, historical, and individual preferences.",
